The banks want to solve the crisis
The Federal Reserve of American reserve, the European Central Bank and the central banks English, Swiss and Canadian have decided to work together to combat the crisis of the financial markets.
More than one hundred billion dollars will be placed on the money markets by the Intermédiare of auctions.
It will be for banks to sell, by a system of auctions, interest rates Auquels they are prepared to borrow money.
For example, the EDF American will send at auction $40 billion and, furthermore, it will provide 24 billion to European central banks and Switzerland.
This is the first time since the attacks of 11 September that the central banks of individual States have determined action so concerted, to prevent or reduce the effects of the financial crisis.
"This tends to resolve the major problems of the economy growing, namely the lack of free capital that banks could pay', writes in his report to clients Bernard Baumohl society Council economic outlook group.
"The concerted action by central banks has diminished the likelihood of a recession in the United States of 65% to about 50%," adds Baumohl in his report.
The banks have already lost 60 billion dollars because loans not repaid, especially in the US.
Analysts expect further losses in billion.
"If central banks have chosen this approach is that they should really grasp what can be successful," said the chief economist of the AMRO agitated Kieran Davies.
"It seems that the situation is really bad", adds.
Central banks fear that, if the banks themselves will have a difficult access to loans, they will pay more to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the US economy into recession can influence the economic growth of the world.
The central banks have made this choice after it has failed to bring down the interbank rate of London, called Libor, used to borrow on the interbank market.
Which meant that banks feared always borrowing mutual, despite the fact that the central banks American, Canadian and English have fallen on several occasions, in the autumn, their interest rates.
"This will have the same effect that a further cut in interest rates," said the Reuters news agency Greg Salvaggio society Tempus consulting.
Some analysts do not believe that the approach of the central banks nothing to avert the crisis, since it does not solve the main problem which is the fall of the property market in the United States.
