They have failed on Wednesday an agreement on the future status of the province, at the last session of negotiations in Vienna.
In the end, the failure.
The Serbs and Albanians in Kosovo have completed Wednesday morning in Baden, Austria, a sixth and final sitting of discussions without having been able to overcome their differences on the future status of the separatist province.
"It is regrettable that the parties have not been able to reach an agreement on the status, said the European Ombudsman Wolfgang Ischinger, at a press conference in Vienna.
Stressing that peace in the region was at stake, its American counterpart, frank Wisner, has called on Belgrade and Pristina to respect their commitments to preserve peace and dialogue beyond the end of the negotiations.
"It does not provide for violence in the immediate future but we are entering a very difficult period", he added, is that "obvious tensions exist'.
End of mediation on 10 December
The Ombudsmen of the troika, which includes the European Union, the United States and Russia, will make a last time Monday in Serbia and Kosovo.
The future of the province with a population of 90% Albanians may become more clear when Ischinger, Wisner and the Ombudsman Russian Alexander Botsane-khartchenko will their report to the Security Council of the United Nations, between now and December 10.
The discussions in Baden, near Vienna, was the sixth and last session of negotiations since the troika was given the task of a new mediation by the UN, last August.
Americans and Europeans see that their mediation will end on 10 December.
The Russians, who have already blocked in the Security Council the granting of independence in Kosovo, they insist on a further negotiations beyond the deadline.
"Russia was and remains committed to a negotiated solution, a compromise solution", said Botsane-khartchenko.
Unilateral declaration of independence?
After eight years of UN administration of Kosovo, the Western believe that the independence under supervision of the EU is the only viable solution.
Pristina is ready to declare unilaterally if the Security Council tranche not in favour of it.
Belgrade is insisting on a greater autonomy.
"Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached," announced the President of the autonomous authority in Kosovo, as Sejdiu, in the hotel of Baden where being held since Monday these "negotiations of the last chance."
Postulated Thaci, former Commander of the rebellion Kosovo and future Prime Minister of the province, has expressed its regret.
But he added that the plan of autonomy presented by Belgrade "belonged to a past which has led to murders and deportations.
' domino effect'
The Serbian President Boris Tadic has estimated that a compromise was still possible, warning Kosovo's Albanian majority against the consequences of a unilateral proclamation of the independence of the province.
Belgrade said in particular fear a "domino effect" in a region still weakened by the independence wars of the 1990s.
"For Serbia, he said, this does not mean that a compromise is impossible."
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation had insisted that any decision to return exclusively to the Security Council, where its ally Russian has a right of veto.
"The Parliament of Kosovo will have the last word'
"only a solution within the Security Council is acceptable to Serbia," said the Serbian Prime Minister, Vojislav Kostunica.
"These negotiations have lasted two years.
They must come to an end as they began: the Security Council. "
Journalists, as Sedjiu had replied that "the Parliament of Kosovo will be the last word on the statute", adding that any unilateral declaration of independence by the Albanians would be "in consultation" with the West.
Bush is pulling out an agreement between Israelis and Palestinians
President George Bush announced, at the opening of the international peace conference met by its care on Tuesday at Annapolis, Maryland, the Israelis and the Palestinians had finally agreed on a joint declaration.
He said that the Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Olmert and Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas had agreed to begin immediate negotiations with a view to reaching a final settlement of the dispute old 60 years between their two peoples.
In the presence of the two men, Bush has promised that he would do everything to help them to conclude a "Peace Treaty" before the end of 2008.
In the meantime, the Palestinians must dismantle "the terrorist infrastructure" and Israel must stop its settlement activity, Bush said, recalling the two sides to their obligations with regard to the "road map" for peace that they have accepted in 2003.
The head of the White House has stressed that the negotiations between Israel and the Palestinian authority led by Abbas aimed "to conclude a peace treaty resolving all the outstanding issues, without exception, including the central issues".
This designation covers the three difficult issues at the heart of the dispute between Israelis and Palestinians: the future borders of Palestine, the status of Jerusalem and the fate of Arab refugees driven from their homes in what is now the State of Israel in the conflict in 1948.
Taking the floor after the American President, Abbas has insisted that the forthcoming negotiations are "comprehensive and thorough" and relate to all aspects of a regulation, citing "Jerusalem, refugees, borders, settlements, water, security, among other".
Amount to turn to the gallery, Olmert has promised that the coming talks are "direct and continuous" and "an effort to complete in the course of 2008."
Bush has set at the end of the year 2008 the deadline for implementation of his "vision of two states" Palestinian and Israeli coexist.
Saudi Arabia revealed that it had obtained a commitment in this direction of Bush before deciding to participate in the Conference.
Arabia, whose participation in Annapolis is a success for Washington, is at the root of a plan, endorsed by all the Arab countries, which proposes peace to Israel in exchange for its withdrawal from all the occupied Arab territories during the 1967 war, including East Jerusalem.
Annapolis "marks a crossroads in the history of the Middle East, in particular because it addresses the root causes of conflict and its central aspects", according to Prince Saud in his interview on a daily basis Non-Arab-speaking to Saudi capital.
