The tension is rising in Pakistan
The Pakistani police has put down on Monday the first demonstrations since the establishment of the state of emergency two days ago by General Musharraf.
In the city of Lahore, to the east of the country, around 2, 000 lawyers who were demonstrating against the measures taken in the framework of the state of emergency were injured by the grenades tear gas used by the forces of law and order, according to witnesses.
They have retaliated by stones, injuring policemen.
At least 350 lawyers have been questioned.
Similar scenarios in Karachi and Rawalpindi, or police have charged and injured lawyers.
Several would have been questioned.
Has Islamabad, lawyers of the bar of the Supreme Court have called for a general strike and announced demonstrations, following a wave of almost 500 arrests over the weekend of opponents, human rights activists and lawyers.
The streets giving access to the Supreme Court were blocked on Monday morning to prevent the Assembly.
Other demonstrations would have taken place to Multan (centre) and Peshawar (north-west).
The movement of lawyers on Monday won the support of religious parties grouped in the powerful alliance Muttahida Majlis-e-Amal which President "has urged people to send flowers to the judges who voted against the state of emergency and rubbish to those who have sworn to Musharraf".
"The promise of Musharraf takes more'
The Pakistan Supreme Court is directly covered by the measure of exception declared Saturday evening.
In the next few days to decide on the legality of the presidential re-election, on 6 October, suffrage indirect, of President Musharraf.
The President of the Court, chief Mohammed Chaudhry, was ousted and replaced.
"All what we are seeing is illegal, unconstitutional and contrary to the judgments of the Supreme Court," the magistrate said in the newspaper the news.
The promise of Pervez Musharraf to leave the head of the army and become a civilian president will no longer be relevant "after the establishment of the state of emergency, said on Monday the Ministre-adjoint information Tariq Azeem.
He abandons his military uniform expected by 15 November, the date of the end of his first presidential term.
The Ministre-adjoint information has also confirmed that the January elections could be postponed.
Moreover, the Pakistani Government has denied rumours insistent in the country that President Musharraf would have been under house arrest by his chief deputy armies.
