The Bank of England takes note of the concerns by offering 10 billion pounds in five weeks
The Bank of England on Thursday expressed keen to lighten the return of current concern about the conditions of credit, and has announced an offer of 10 billion pounds in the base rate of 5.75% over five weeks, an offer lasting unusual.
"To alleviate the concerns that the conditions of the financial market will be particularly tight at the end of the year, and to give the banks greater certainty in how they organise their liquidity positions on this period, the Bank intends to offer a significant proportion of its contribution reserves provided during the period of maintenance starting on 6 December in the form of an operation to open market to five weeks", teach in a statement.
The Bank says that 10 billion pounds (14 billion euros) will be placed on the market and on 6 December at 12.15 p.m GMT, the base rate and until 10 January.
This is the first time it seems that the Boe put on the market liquidity to five weeks in an operation to open market.
They are normally a week.
The Boe added in its statement that it "stands ready to take further measures to maintain the rate of inter-bank loans from day to day in line with its base rate.
The interbank rate from day to day was Wednesday of 5,829%.
The rate at three months was established to 6.6%, a higher since 18 September.
Since the beginning of the financial crisis of the summer, are placed on the market by the Bank of England were accompanied by a rate of important penalty which had deterred the banks.
According to some rumours, corroborated by changes in the exchange rate of the pound against the euro, many had preferred to accept are placed on the market by the European Central Bank rates, cheaper and with a discretion longer guaranteed.
