The new case of gas between Russia and Ukraine lays the alarm.
A dispute on the price of gas ferments between Ukraine and Russia, thus increasing the risks of an impact on exports of fuel oil to Europe.
Most of the Russian gas exports to the European Union (U.e) are hauled by pipelines, and each led is strictly monitored.
Kiev has announced that if Russia increases the cost of fuel oil, it will increase taxes transit to Russia.
Last year, a row between the two, had caused a reduction of supplies to the countries of the U.e.
The last dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes after the Ukrainian Government and Gazprom, society monopoly property of Russia providing gas, have tried in vain to reach agreement on the cost of Russian gas supplied to Ukraine for the year 2008.
Gazprom has said that he would increase as planned, its prices to Ukraine because it has agreed to pay for 2008, up to 50% more for gas supplies from the neighbouring Turkmenistan.
Analysts have said that this would for Ukraine, an increase of 40% of the costs of imports from Gazprom.
"It is essential for us to use all our arguments during the talks, pointing out that we are a country through which passes the most gas," announced the Ukrainian Minister of the economy, Anatoly Kinkh to the Reuters news agency.
"The fluctuations cost of gas would probably linked to our discussions about taxes transit (to Western Europe) via Ukraine'
The last major row between Moscow and Kiev has caused in January 2006, the interruption of Gazprom supplies to Ukraine.
This led to the fall of exports to Western Europe, therefore increasing prices.
The Russian gas accounts for a quarter of supplies to the European Union.
Russia has the largest stocks of gas, even though most of them are still under developed.
Therefore, Gazprom complete its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other nations of the former Soviet Union in Central Asia.
The Ministry of Health' must control its employees foreigners'.
The Ministry of Health Scottish must improve the controls to be carried out on its employees Non-Community to check if they have previous criminal, said the Committee of control.
The warning of the auditor general, Robert Black, took place after a doctor foreign working in Scotland, was involved in the attack at the airport in Glasgow in June.
Mr Black has also expressed its concern that the Ministry of Health Scottish has no exact information on the number of people overseas that it employs.
His report has highlighted other controls decisive, properly carried out on a sample of employees of five health authorities.
The auditor general has made controls on the staff Non-Community following the attack on the airport Glasgow.
Bilal Addullah, 28 years, doctor of origin Iraqi in the service of the hospital Royal Alexandra of Paisley, was arrested at the airport after dark with its jeep, in the doors of the main terminal.
It was the party of three doctors who have been filmed in the old Bailey in October, because suspected of being involved in various attempts explosion of cars in the United Kingdom.
The Ministry of Health will carry out controls meadow employment on the staff overseas, to ensure the validity of their qualifications, experience, and work permits for the United Kingdom.
Although the Ministry of Health Scottish use the disclosure Ecossaise to carry out checks of previous criminal, the Agency has no right to receive such information outside of Britain.
Among the many warnings, the report of the auditor general says now that the committees are obliged to confront with the Bureau of control of previous criminal, thus enabling the employers to carry out checks on various countries.
"Although we have discovered that some information about the staff have been verified, this is done every time.' announcement the report.
Mr Black said that the Ministry of Health Scottish carried out most controls meadow employment that he would do itself, but it has also added: "our report highlights aspects where the system can be improved to ensure that appropriate information on some members of staff overseas are available to health services.
Mr Peter Terry, chairman of Bma Scotland has said that it is "extremely unlikely" that controls meadow employment can identify employees likely to commit future acts of terrorism.
He says "the report suggests that controls meadow employment carried out currently, work well in the Scottish health system and that it is not certain that these warnings can make any added value."
The Scottish health authorities have said use 1161 people overseas, made up mostly of doctors and nurses.
But the auditor general pointed out that these figures should certainly be adjusted upwards, partly because of problems relating to the identification of members of staff with contracts of indefinite duration, which could choose or not, to stay in our country.
The investigation has shown that the current procedures of controls on health authorities to Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian, are quite adequate.
