Fraud of cards.
The crisis of mortgages Contaminerait-elle the American market credit cards?
When there is blood in the water, it is normal to see fins artificially, Tourbillonner around.
Now that the US home market is going through a critical phase, the predators are aimed at the American market credit cards.
Analysts from home Goldman Sachs believe that the losses relating to credit cards could reach $99 billion if the infection mortgages extends to other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of tension are clearly visible.
There are increases in rates of costs and insolvency, which measure the share of assessment not recoverable or which are more than 30 days after.
HSBC announced last month that he took $1.4 billion in its funds to consumers, in part because of the weakness of the bearers.
It is too early to panic.
The costs and the insolvencies are still moderate.
According to Moody, an agency tax, the rate of insolvency of 3,89% of Troixième quarter is lower than almost a point in relation to its historical average.
The deterioration rates is understandable in part by technical factors.
A change laws in 2005 in the US, on the personal bankruptcy has caused a fall abrupt archives of bankruptcy, which in turn has caused heavy losses for credit cards; the number of archives (and therefore rates of insolvency) could increase even if the conditions of loans to get worse.
The industry heralds rate fixed payment, which highlight the amount of debt monthly that consumers must resolve.
Sureté and trust in the capital of credit cards is strong enough despite the paralysis other aspects of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of Towergroup, a society of research, has predicted that the volume of emission for 2007 will be 25% higher than last year.
The infection direct links between the crisis of mortgages and the market for credit cards certainly exist: consumers might prefer to increase their indebtedness now that the mortgage fair have disappeared.
But the card industry are more attention to the flow of species rather than the value of heritage, and therefore the fall in home prices has not necessarily led to a change in the credibility of borrowers.
They may even bring benefits issuers of securities credit.
Premiums consumers for the payment of mortgages fall if the properties cost less than the value of the loan; therefore, debt by credit card would become a priority for repay.
The card industry are able to respond much more rapidly than mortgage and more flexibility in such conditions of crisis, because they can change interest rates or alter the limits of Rédit.
This should in theory reduce the risk of an early resumption of actions.
"We are not going we wake up one morning and reassess all loans." Said Gary Perlin, the director of capital one.
If a disaster financial market credit cards is unlikely, there is a strong risk for a reduction.
If the lower prices of real estate and a contraction in the credit market lead America to the recession, the industry will certainly face a future macabre.
