Buses bring people back to work, and to fight against Al Qaeda.
The first bus full of Iraqi refugees from Syria came to Baghdad yesterday, dumping these exiles without money or without visa renewals, or others who hope that the city has returned to normal.
Some have returned to fight against the militants who have away from home.
Has the station bus Mansur, even before the arrival of Damascus 800 people transported in convoys of dozens of buses government official, the terminal was full of refugees in Syria and Jordan who have returned by their means.
"I have decided to go to Syria after they have killed several doctors to Baghdas" said Sabah, a doctor Al-qubaisi Sunni.
"I returned today because I saw on the TV and read in the newspapers what has happened to Baghdâd and since the city is safer now."
"they say that the Mahdi army is committing more crimes!' he said, referring to the militia of Shia militant Church Moqtada Al-Sadr, which has imposed on his men to remove at the moment.
Qassim Al Atwani, a Shia teacher of 38 years in the area of Amariyah dominated by Sunni, returned with his two children, because it could no longer renew his visa Syrian and because the regime prevents the Iraqi to work.
Its neighbouring Shia to Amariyah have called to inform her that the militia helped by the US, has made it possible to hunt Al Qaeda in the west of the capital, and have asked to return.
One of the new entrants of Jordan is the head of a tribe Sunni and Shia who has had to leave his House in Northern Baghdâd because of a grenade attack after he has led the people to revolt against Al-Qaeda.
But he had to return to combat.
"Two days ago, some of my friends called me and told me to have set up a militia anti Al-Qaeda to Sleikh, and that they needed to me and to my boys."
"That is why I returned today," said Sabaah Alu Obeidi, 62 years.
Many say that they have attracted by the growing calm in the capital since US troops arrived, and to the training of groups of citizens' involved' well armed and working together with the US military to defend their neighbourhood.
But still others say have been forced to return because of the problem of visa and decadence of the capital of Damascus, where more than 1.3 million Iraqi have fled the past years.
Salaam Al-samarrai, 51 years, father of three children, has expressed the suspicion felt by all on visas for exiles that Nouri Al-Maliki, the Shia Prime Minister, which would have asked the Syrian Government to limit to force people to return.
More than two and a half million people have fled the country because of sectarian squads of death.
"We had no problem until Al-Maliki Vienna in Syria and encourages the government to give visas to Iraqi, forcing them to return to Iraq" said the pensioner Sunni.
"I can not trust a government that supports the criminals who burnt my House when I left."
The drop in violence can be partly explained by the fact that the Sunnis have been driven out of areas of Shia and vice versa, creating places where tensions are minimal.
It is feared that a sudden flows of refugees increase again sectarian tensions and back the fighting.
